# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2011-welsh-devolution-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The **1832 United Kingdom general election in Wales** was the first election held under the Reform Act 1832 and the Parliamentary Boundaries Act 1832.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] Wales saw its numbers of Members increased from 27 to 32, which includes Monmouthshire, which at the time was sometimes considered part of England.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1832-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The Whigs, under the leadership of the Earl Grey won 18 seats (12 uncontested), against 14 (11 uncontested) for the Duke of Wellington's Tories.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The **1835 United Kingdom general election in Wales** was held in early 1835, as the Sir Robert Peel's newly formed Conservative Party sought to strengthen its position in Parliament.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] The Whigs, under the leadership of the Viscount Melbourne, despite losing 98 seats, survived in the majority through an alliance with the Irish Radicals.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1835-united-kingdom-general-election-in-wales] In Wales specifically, The Whigs won 15 seats (11 uncontested), against 17 (11 uncontested) for the Conservatives, a shift of 3 seats from Whigs to Conservatives.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1837 United Kingdom general election** was held from 24 July to 18 August 1837, following the death of King William IV and the accession of Queen Victoria.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The election saw the Whigs secure their fourth consecutive victory, though the Conservatives, led by Robert Peel, continued to gain ground.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The election marked the last time that a Parliament was dissolved as a result of the demise of the Crown.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1837-united-kingdom-general-election] The dissolution of Parliament six months after a demise of the Crown, as provided for by the Succession to the Crown Act 1707, was abolished by the Reform Act 1867.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1841 United Kingdom general election** was held between 29 June and 22 July 1841.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] Following increasing government defeats, the Conservatives under Sir Robert Peel won a decisive victory against the governing Whigs.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives campaigned mainly on an 11-point programme modified from their previous electoral effort and designed by Peel, whilst the Whigs emphasised reforming the import duties on corn, replacing the existing sliding scale with a uniform rate.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whig position lost them support amongst protectionists, and the Whigs saw heavy losses in constituencies like the West Riding, where aristocratic Whig families who held a strong tradition of unbroken representation in Parliament were rejected by the electorate.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] O'Connell, who had been governing with the Whigs through a compact, felt the government's unpopularity rub off on him.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] His own party was shattered in the election.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] Barely a dozen Repealers retained their seats, and O'Connell himself lost in Dublin while his son was defeated in Carlow.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1841-united-kingdom-general-election] The Chartists picked up only a few votes.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1847 United Kingdom general election** was held from 29 July to 26 August 1847.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] It saw the Conservatives win the most seats but remain divided between Protectionists and Peelites.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] This allowed the Whigs, led by Prime Minister Lord John Russell, to retain power.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election was held amid the Great Irish famine.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The Irish Repeal group won more seats than in the previous general election, while the Chartists gained the only seat they were ever to hold, Nottingham's second seat, held by Chartist leader Feargus O'Connor.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The election also witnessed the election of Britain's first Jewish MP, the Liberal Lionel de Rothschild in the City of London.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] Members being sworn in were however required to swear the Christian Oath of Allegiance, meaning Rothschild was unable actually to take his seat until the passage of the Jews Relief Act in 1858.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of Sudbury, which elected two members, was disfranchised for this election.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1847-united-kingdom-general-election] This accounts there being two fewer seats in the House of Commons as compared to the previous election, though no redistribution took place.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1852 United Kingdom general election** was held from 7 to 31 July 1852.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] It produced a closely contested result between the Conservatives and Whigs, marking a significant shift in British politics, with the Conservatives increasingly representing the rural aristocracy and the Whigs the urban bourgeoisie.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] As in the previous election of 1847, Lord John Russell's Whigs won the popular vote, but the Conservative Party won a very slight majority of the seats.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] However, a split between Protectionist Tories, led by the Earl of Derby, and the Peelites who supported Lord Aberdeen made the formation of a majority government very difficult.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Lord Derby's minority, protectionist government ruled from 23 February until 17 December 1852.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Derby appointed Benjamin Disraeli as Chancellor of the Exchequer in this minority government.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] However, in December 1852, Derby's government collapsed because of issues arising out of the budget introduced by Disraeli.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] A Peelite–Whig-Radical coalition government was then formed under Lord Aberdeen.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Although the immediate issue involved in this vote of "no confidence" which caused the downfall of the Derby minority government was the budget, the real underlying issue was the repeal of the Corn Laws which Parliament had passed in June 1846 and had split the Conservative Party.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In this election, there were 18 Peelites elected in England and Wales.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The constituency of St Albans, with its two members, was disfranchised due to corruption.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This accounts for the fact that there were two fewer seats in the House of Commons as compared to the previous election, though no redistribution took place.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] A group within the Tory/Conservative Party called the "Peelites" voted with the Whigs to achieve the repeal of the Corn Laws.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Peelites were so named because they were followers of Prime Minister Robert Peel.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In June 1846, when Peel was the Prime Minister of a Tory government, he led a group of Tory/Conservatives to vote with the minority Whigs against a majority of his own party.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] "Corn" was important to the cost of living of the average person in Britain during the early 19th century.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The term "corn" did not refer to maize, as it did in the United States.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In Britain, "corn" refers to wheat, rye and/or other grains.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Wheat, or corn, was used in the baking of bread and was the "staff of life".
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Thus the price of wheat was a very substantial part of the cost of living.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Corn Laws enforced a very high "protective" tariff against the importation of wheat into England.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] These high tariffs raised the cost of living and increased the suffering of poor people in England.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Agitation for the repeal of the Corn Laws had begun in England as early as 1837, and bills for their repeal had been introduced in Parliament each year from 1837 until their actual repeal in 1847.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] For some parliamentary leaders, like John Bright, Richard Cobden and Charles Pelham Villiers, the repeal of tariffs on imported corn was not enough.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] They wished to reduce the tariffs on all imported consumer products.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] These parliamentary leaders became known as "free traders".
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The repeal of the Corn Laws irrevocably split the Tory/Conservative party.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Peelites were not free traders, but both the Peelites and the free traders were originally Tories.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Thus both the free traders and the Peelites tended to side with the Whigs against the Tories on international trade issues.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This presented a real threat to any government the Tories attempted to form.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The effect of this split was felt in the election of July–August 1847, when the Whig party won a 53.8% majority of seats in Parliament.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs knew that they could count on the Peelite Conservatives when an international trade issue came before Parliament.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In June 1852, the effects of the split in the Tory/Conservative party was having even more effect.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The period after about 1847 was one of economic stagnation in Britain.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The split in the Tory party was a significant cause of the reformation of the political parties in Britain in the February 1852 election.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] As noted above, in the election of 1852 the protectionist rump of the Conservatives became the party of the rural landholders, while the Liberals and Peelites became the party of the towns, boroughs and growing urban industrial areas of Britain.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1852, England elected 244 Conservatives and 216 non-Conservatives; Wales elected 20 Conservatives and 12 non-Conservatives, Scotland elected 20 Conservatives and 33 non-Conservatives, Ireland elected 40 Conservatives and 63 non-Conservatives whereas the Universities elected 6 Conservatives.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The election of 1852 returned a majority in support of free-trade, but the minority Conservative government continued in office.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] An opportunity for the opposition arose in December 1852, when the Chancellor of the Exchequer, Benjamin Disraeli, introduced the budget of the Derby minority government.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Due to the worsening economic situation, the budget imposed a number of tax increases on the profits of the middle class and granted some tax cuts for the rural landed aristocracy.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The budget also extended the income tax to the Irish middle class, angering some of the members from Ireland who had supported the minority government on the Irish Church issue and were opposed to the previous Prime Minister, the Liberal leader Lord John Russell.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Consequently, a number of Irish Conservatives voted against the minority government on the Disraeli budget on 17 December 1852.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This vote of "no confidence" caused the government to fall.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the fall of the minority government, Lord Aberdeen was called on to form a government, since the Irish Conservatives who opposed Disraeli's budget were opposed to Lord John Russell on religious issues and he formed a Peelite/Whig coalition government on 19 December 1852.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] This government served until 30 January 1855, when it too collapsed due to issues surrounding British involvement in the Crimean War.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] While the Conservatives had, in theory, a slim majority over the Whigs, the party was divided between Protectionist and Peelite wings: the former numbered about 290 and the latter 35–40.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The Whigs themselves represented a coalition of old Whigs (conservative Protestant/dissenter aristocrats), Liberals, Radicals, and Irish nationalists.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1852-united-kingdom-general-election] The above numbers therefore do not represent the true balance of support in Parliament.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The **1859 United Kingdom general election** was held from 28 April to 18 May 1859 following the defeat of Prime Minister the Earl of Derby's Conservative government in a vote of confidence.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The newly formed Liberal Party, led by Viscount Palmerston, secured victory despite winning fewer seats than in the previous election.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] There is no separate tally of votes or seats for the Peelites.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] They did not contest elections as an organised party but more as independent Free trade Conservatives with varying degrees of distance from the two main parties.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the last general election entered by the Chartists, before their organisation was dissolved.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] As of 2024, this is the last election in which the Conservatives won the most seats in Wales.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was the quietest and least competitive between 1832 and 1885, with most county elections being uncontested.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] The election also saw the lowest number of candidates between 1832 and 1885, with Tory gains potentially being the result of a lack of opposition as much as a change in public opinion.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] the government which Palmerston organized in June 1859 was a coalition of a different kind: not a coalition of groups which looked back to the past, but a coalition which anticipated the future.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] Had it not been for Palmerston himself—too individual, too full of personality to be fitted into a party-pattern—it would have been the first Liberal government in our history.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/1859-united-kingdom-general-election] Everything that was important in it was Liberal—finance, administrative reform, its very composition: the first government with unmistakable middle-class Free Traders as members.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] A **referendum on the powers of the National Assembly for Wales** was held on 3 March 2011.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Voters were asked whether the Assembly should have full law-making powers in the twenty subject areas where it has jurisdiction.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] If a majority voted 'yes', the Assembly would then be able to make laws, known as Acts of the Assembly, on all matters in the subject areas, without needing the UK Parliament's agreement.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] If a majority voted 'no', the arrangements at the time of the referendum would have continued – that is, in each devolved area, the Assembly would be able to make its own laws on some matters, but not others.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] To make laws on any of these other matters, the Assembly would have had to ask the UK Parliament to transfer the powers to it.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Regulations for the referendum, and the powers to be approved or rejected by it, were provided for in the Government of Wales Act 2006.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results of the referendum were announced on 4 March 2011.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] In 21 of 22 local authorities the vote was 'yes', with the exception being Monmouthshire by a slim majority.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] While the referendum was technically non-binding, it gave the Welsh Government the statutory authority to make a ministerial order triggering the relevant changes in the Assembly's powers.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The order was duly made on 30 March and came into force on 5 May 2011, the day of the quadrennial Assembly election.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Part IV of the Government of Wales Act 2006 provided for the National Assembly for Wales to pass Acts instead of Measures.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Acts required only the consent of the Assembly, whereas Measures required a Legislative Competence Order involving the United Kingdom's Secretary of State for Wales, Parliament, and Privy Council.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] However, Part IV could not come into force unless an order was made by the Welsh Government after a referendum of Welsh voters.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The two parties agreed "in good faith to campaign for a successful outcome to such a referendum" and to set up an All-Wales Convention to prepare for such a successful outcome.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 27 October 2007 the then First Minister Rhodri Morgan and the Deputy First Minister Ieuan Wyn Jones appointed Sir Emyr Jones Parry, the recently retired Permanent Representative from Britain to the United Nations to head the convention.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Sir Emyr stated on 22 November 2007 that he would like to begin to work as soon as possible and hoped to have the report ready by 2009 at the latest.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The All Wales Convention reported to the First Minister and the Deputy First Minister on 18 November 2009.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] It reported that a "yes" vote would be obtainable but not guaranteed.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] An opinion poll for the convention had found that 47% would vote Yes, and 37% would vote No.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The report suggested that the Assembly needed to decide before June 2010 whether to trigger a referendum if the vote was to be held before the next Assembly elections.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 2 February 2010 the new First Minister Carwyn Jones, who had succeeded Rhodri Morgan on 9 December 2009, confirmed that a trigger vote would be held on 9 February on whether the Assembly should request a referendum on full law making powers.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The Welsh Liberal Democrats and Welsh Conservatives stated they did not want the referendum to be held on the same day as the 2011 Assembly elections and would abstain from voting to trigger the referendum if this date was not ruled out.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The trigger vote was held in the Assembly on Tuesday 9 February 2010, and was approved unanimously across all parties, with 53 out of the 60 AMs voting for it.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Under the Government of Wales Act 2006 the First Minister was required to send a letter within two weeks to the Welsh Secretary (then Peter Hain), who would then have 120 days to lay a draft order for a referendum before Parliament.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] It was expected that the referendum date would not be set until after the general election.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 15 June 2010 Cheryl Gillan, the new Welsh Secretary in the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government at Westminster, announced that the referendum would probably be held between January and March 2011.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Others proposed that it should be held on 5 May 2011, together with both the Assembly elections and the AV referendum.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] It was agreed that the referendum be held on 3 March 2011, after representations to the Welsh Secretary from the Welsh Government.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] This wording was, however, criticised by the Welsh Government.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] permitting a simple **YES** / **NO** answer (to be marked with a single (X)).
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] In 2007, one poll suggested that 47% might say Yes in a referendum vote, with 44% against.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] A poll in February 2008 saw 49% in favour of a full law-making parliament and 41% against.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] On 3 February 2010 the *Western Mail* endorsed the Yes campaign.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] A BBC poll released on 1 March 2010 (St.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] David's Day) found that support had risen for full law making powers, up to 56%, with 35% against, although Welsh Conservative leader Nick Bourne (who supported a yes vote) was sceptical of the poll results.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] A summary table of poll results in advance of the referendum is set out below.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The results were counted and announced the following day on Friday 4 March 2011, locally initially with the final result declared at the Senedd in Cardiff by the Chair of the Electoral Commission Jenny Watson who announced the result in both Welsh and English.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] In 21 of 22 unitary authorities, the vote was **Yes**.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The only counting area to declare a **No** result was Monmouthshire, which was announced following a recount.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Turnout was highest in Carmarthenshire (44.36%) and lowest in Wrexham (27.04%).
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] The highest percentage of **Yes** votes was in Gwynedd (76.03% Yes) and the highest percentage of **No** votes was in Monmouthshire (50.64% No).
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Deputy First Minister and Plaid Cymru leader Ieuan Wyn Jones said that it marked "the beginning of a new era of Welsh devolution - the decade to deliver for Wales. ...
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] To demand respect, you must first display self-respect.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Kirsty Williams, leader of the Welsh Liberal Democrats, said that the referendum showed that people "wanted to endorse and strengthen devolution", but they "also want it to work better".
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] She said that voters were right to show "widespread dissatisfaction" with the Welsh Government's performance.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Welsh Secretary Cheryl Gillan, a member of the Conservative Party, said that there had been concern over turnout, but called it "a good day for Wales".
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] She said that the UK Government would reinforce its commitment to make the arrangements work effectively.
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] Rachel Banner, of the No campaign, said that it marked a "turning point for our nation".
[src:2011-welsh-devolution-referendum/2011-welsh-devolution-referendum] She questioned the legitimacy of the result, asking: "Has it got the full-hearted consent of the Welsh people?" She also stated that she did not believe that the 42 backbench members of the Assembly could provide high-quality scrutiny of the activities of the Welsh Government.
